  "prompt": "What is import substitution? Has it ever worked? Is it generally accepted that export substitution is the superior economic theory for developing nations?",
  "response": "Import substitution industrialization (ISI) and export-oriented industrialization are two different economic development strategies. Let me break down the details:\n\nImport Substitution:\n- Economic development strategy where countries aim to reduce foreign dependency by producing domestically what was previously imported\n- Typically involves high tariffs and trade barriers to protect domestic industries\n- Common in Latin America during 1950s-1980s (e.g., Brazil, Argentina, Mexico)\n\nSuccesses:\n- Helped develop domestic manufacturing capabilities\n- Reduced vulnerability to global economic shifts\n- Created industrial infrastructure in some countries\n\nFailures:\n- Often led to inefficient, uncompetitive industries\n- Created high consumer prices\n- Limited technological innovation\n- Resulted in economic stagnation\n\nExport Orientation:\n- Focuses on producing goods for international markets\n- Emphasizes comparative advantage and global competitiveness\n- Successfully implemented by Asian tigers (South Korea, Taiwan, Singapore)\n\nGenerally Accepted View:\nMost economists now believe export-oriented strategies are more effective because they:\n- Encourage efficiency and innovation\n- Provide access to larger markets\n- Drive technological advancement\n- Attract foreign investment\n\nWhile import substitution isn't entirely discredited, export orientation is widely considered the superior development strategy for most developing nations.",
